Here is my solution. The idea is following: 
1. build a map for arr, with value -> index pair. so to get look up time with O(1).
2.Iterate every number in every piece, check if the current element is in the map or not. 
  2.1 if not in map, return false
 2.2 if in map, get the index for this number in arr, compare this index with the previous iterations index, make sure previousElementOriginalIndex + 1 = currentElementOriginalIndex. Also update the previousElementOriginalIndex = currentElementOriginalIndex so it can be used in the next iteration. this would make sure the order can be match with the order in the arr. Also remember to remove the current element from the map incase pieces might have duplicated numbers(essentially if pieces contains duplicate number, it could fail fast since we know arr has distinct values).
3. return map.size() == 0 if map not empty, meaning there are elements not matched, so we fail.

```
 public boolean canFormArr(int[] arr, int[][] pieces){
        // arr: value -> index
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++){
            map.put(arr[i], i);
        }

        for(int[] piece: pieces){
            // maintain the index from the original array, as for each piece we need to guarantee the order.
            int previousElementOriginalIndex = -1;

            for(int n: piece){
                int currentElementOriginalIndex = map.getOrDefault(n, -1);
                //element not exist in map
                if(currentElementOriginalIndex == -1){
                    return false;
                }

                if(previousElementOriginalIndex == -1){
                    previousElementOriginalIndex = currentElementOriginalIndex;
                    // remove n from map in case duplicate, since the question 
                    // didin't mention if pieces would contain distinct value.
                    map.remove(n);
                }else if (currentElementOriginalIndex == previousElementOriginalIndex+ 1) {
                    // remove n from map in case duplicate, since the question 
                    // didin't mention if pieces would contain distinct value.
                    map.remove(n);
                    previousElementOriginalIndex = currentElementOriginalIndex;
                }else{
                    // if currentElementOriginalIndex != previousElementOriginalIndex+ 1, meaning the order didn't match, reutrn false;
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }
        // we know arr contains distinct value, but pieces may not

        return map.size() == 0;
    }
